==== Methodological Problems with the EEfRT

The Effort-Expenditure for Rewards Task (EEfRT) was designed to measure motivation for rewards in psychiatric conditions, with an explicit requirement that tasks be easy enough that fatigue does not confound results. In the Walitt study:
    - ME/CFS patients completed only 65% of hard trials vs.\ 96–99% for controls
    - Seven of 15 patients performed below any control participant
    - Physical function scores (SF-36) were 28.7 for patients vs.\ 97.5 for controls
Kirvin-Quamme et al.'s reanalysis @kirvinquamme2025effort demonstrated a significant correlation between task completion ability and task choice, indicating the tool measured ability, not preference. Their conclusion: patients were “unable,” not “unwilling.”

